description: From Middle English overholden, from Old English oferhealdan (“to overcome, overtake, hold over, delay to do, neglect”), from Proto-Germanic *uber (“over”) + *haldaną (“to hold”), equivalent to over- +‎ hold. Cognate with Dutch overhouden (“to hang on, hold over, save”), German überhalten (“to hold on to, keep”), Danish overholde (“to observe”).

entries.meaning: The act or process of holding over.
examples: Overholding clauses serve the purpose of contractually regulating the terms and conditions of an overhold.

verbs.description: overhold (third-person singular simple present overholds, present participle overholding, simple past overheld, past participle overheld or overholden)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To overvalue; overestimate; hold or estimate at too dear a rate.
examples: That is your opinion: you state here that you were induced to overhold the land  […]
